	\item Let $\mu$ be the mean run time of the hot-plates in minutes. 
	\textit{Null Hypothesis}: $\mu\leq 480$ and \textit{Alternative Hypothesis}: $\mu>480$.
	We use the procedure for a right-tailed test as discussed in problem 2(b). We calculate
	\[
		P\qty(Z\geq\sqrt{50}\cdot\frac{485-480}{30}) = P\qty(Z\geq\frac{\sqrt{50}}{6})>P(Z\geq 1.18)
	\]
	Using the provided table, $P(Z\leq 1.18) = 0.8810$, so $P(Z\geq 1.18) = 1 - 0.8810 = 0.1190$. 
	Since $0.1190 > 0.05$ (our level of significance), we accept the null hypothesis and conclude that there is not enough evidence to support the claim that the mean run time is more than 480 minutes.
	
	\item Let $p$ be the proportion of people in the class who listen to Siva.
	\textit{Null Hypothesis}: $p\geq 0.15$ and \textit{Alternative Hypothesis}: $p<0.15$ (Siva's conjecture).
	We use the procedure for a left-tailed test as discussed in problem 2(a). Given the sample mean $\overline{X} = \frac{380}{960}$, sample size $n = 960$, and known variance $\sigma^2 = 2$, we calculate
	\[
		P\qty(Z\leq\sqrt{960}\cdot\frac{\frac{380}{960}-0.15}{\sqrt{2}}) = P\qty(Z\leq\frac{59\sqrt{30}}{60}) > P(Z\leq 5.38)
	\]
	Since $P(Z\leq 5.38) > 0.9998$, the $p$-value is effectively 1. Because the $p$-value is so massive, we would need a significance level $\alpha \approx 1$ to reject it, meaning our confidence level ($1-\alpha$) would be effectively $0\%$.
	Thus, we will not be able to reject the null hypothesis by any reasonable means at all, and we conclude that Siva's conjecture is highly likely to be false.
\end{enumerate}

